english:
  title: On the Meaning of the Name 'Haoran'
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A visitor asked, "Why did Lee Jun change his name from Wonryeong to Jip, and take the courtesy name Haoran? Did he perhaps witness something in his former life that prompted this change?"

    I replied, "No, that is not so. Lee Jun is a man of integrity. External circumstances cannot shake what dwells within him, much less would he alter his true nature on account of adversity. I know well of Lee Jun's trials. When the traitor Shin Don held power, one of Lee Jun's fellow townsmen became his servile associate. Lee Jun, seeing the injustice of his deeds, greatly offended him and faced threats of harm. He fled southward, leading the elderly and carrying children, dwelling in fields and eating grass. Wind, frost, rain, and snow assailed him; bandits, tigers, wolves, insects, and serpents plagued him; hunger, cold, and bitter want pressed upon him. Every hardship known to man crowded into a single life, yet his resolve never wavered. This shows that something within him was cultivated and preserved. When suffering came, he bore it with the weight of Mount Tai—unmoved, untouched. When he overcame it, he moved with the swiftness of a feather in wildfire—leaving no trace. The more he was tested, the more steadfast his will became, like refined metal and precious jade that grow ever more lustrous even under the furnace's heat and the grindstone's wear. Can this not be achieved save by one who has cultivated what lies within?

    Therefore, when Lee Jun changed his name and courtesy name, he sought to honor what he had long nurtured and to strengthen his resolve to keep it. To say he made this change because adversity transformed him is to not truly know Lee Jun."

    The visitor said, "I understand. What then is this cultivation he possesses, and by what method is it maintained?"

    I answered, "Lee Jun now bears the name Jip and the courtesy name Haoran, grounded in the teachings of Mencius. Recently, the scholar Lee of Sungsan wrote a most detailed and illuminating account of Lee Jun's naming; what need have I to add more? Yet I cannot leave your question unaddressed, and so I offer this explanation:

    What we call 'Haoran' is the righteous breath of Heaven and Earth. All things that fill the space between Heaven and Earth obtain this breath as their substance. In spirits it becomes the hidden and manifest; in sun, moon, and stars it becomes illumination; when it strikes, it becomes thunder and lightning; when it moistens, it becomes rain and dew; it forms the peaks of mountains and the flow of rivers and seas; it enables birds, beasts, and vegetation to flourish. Its substance is supremely great and supremely strong—it encompasses the universe with no exterior, penetrates to the finest hair's breadth with no interior. Its movement never ceases; its function extends everywhere. Man receives its most refined essence to live, and so in man, the clarity of ear and eye, the breathing of mouth and nose, the grasping of hand, and the running of foot—all are the work of this breath. Originally, it is inherently complete and lacking nothing, flowing in unison with Heaven and Earth. This is what Lee Jun cultivates.

    Yet the method of this cultivation is no private contrivance or expedient measure. One cannot merely abandon it, nor can one merely assist it through force. One must simply collect righteous acts. When this breath flows in its fullness, neither metal nor stone can withstand it. It does not grow wet in water, does not burn in fire. What strikes it shatters; what confronts it trembles and cracks, unable to resist. How much more so when I, having received this most refined essence to live, further cultivate this most refined essence within my own body as my master and guide? Then what people call suffering—all such things arise from external matters that come from the remainder of this breath. How could they ever harm what is most refined within me? This is why I firmly believe that Lee Jun possesses cultivation within his heart and has altered nothing on account of adversity—of this I have no doubt."

    The visitor responded, "Indeed, indeed," and withdrew. I write this account as a postscript to Lee Jun's naming.
  footnotes:
    - 'Shin Don (辛旽): A powerful Buddhist monk and corrupt official during the Goryeo dynasty who wielded significant political influence, representing the kind of moral corruption that prompted Lee Jun''s flight.'
    - The reference to Mencius is to his concept of 浩然之氣 (haoran zhi qi, the vast, flowing breath of righteousness) from Mencius 2B2, which represents the supreme moral force cultivated through righteous action.
    - The 'method of collecting righteousness' (集義) alludes to Mencius's teaching that this vast breath is nourished through persistent moral action and cannot be forced or abandoned.
